X-SOURCE:IU Maurer School of Law
DTSTART:20260416T213000Z
DTEND:20260416T233000Z
LOCATION:211 South Indiana Avenue Bloomington\, IN 47405 - Room Number: 213
GEO:39.165114;-86.526364
SUMMARY:Applied Research Practicum Presentation
DESCRIPTION:The Applied Research Practicum (https://law.indiana.edu/acade
 mics/experiential-education/practica/legal-systems-in-indiana.html) (ARP)
  is an ongoing access-to-justice project at Maurer Law\, funded in part b
 y the Indiana Supreme Court. During the 2025-26 academic year\, the ARP f
 ocused on designing and building the foundational infrastructure for a pi
 lot nonprofit law firm. This new firm model is designed to provide high-v
 olume\, low-complexity legal services to low- and moderate-income Hoosier
 s. This year's project included process mapping in high-need areas such a
 s family law\, debt collection\, and consumer bankruptcy\; gathering requ
 irements for a core technology platform\; and partnering with a local fam
 ily law court to build an on-site help center to better address the needs
  of pro se litigants  On Thursday\, April 16th at 5:30 pm\, the (ARP) wil
 l present our progress and deliverables to our client\, the Indiana Supre
 me Court's Innovation Committee. Representatives from the Court include R
 obert Rath\, Director of Innovation\, and Justice Derek Molter ('07)\, Ch
 air of the Innovation Committee. The program will last approximately two 
 hours\, with dinner provided. Location: Law School\, Room 213.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The <a href="https://law.indiana.edu/ac
 ademics/experiential-education/practica/legal-systems-in-indiana.html" da
 ta-outlook-id="ff16dd92-2d85-4e18-b0ef-82e69e70c0e7">Applied Research Pra
 cticum</a> (ARP) is an ongoing access-to-justice project at Maurer Law\, 
 funded in part by the Indiana Supreme Court. During the 2025-26 academic 
 year\, the ARP focused on designing and building the foundational infrast
 ructure for a pilot nonprofit law firm. This new firm model is designed t
 o provide high-volume\, low-complexity legal services to low- and moderat
 e-income Hoosiers. This year's project included process mapping in high-n
 eed areas such as family law\, debt collection\, and consumer bankruptcy\
 ; gathering requirements for a core technology platform\; and partnering 
 with a local family law court to build an on-site help center to better a
 ddress the needs of pro se litigants</p><p>  On Thursday\, April 16th at 
 5:30 pm\, the (ARP) will present our progress and deliverables to our cli
 ent\, the Indiana Supreme Court's Innovation Committee. Representatives f
 rom the Court include Robert Rath\, Director of Innovation\, and Justice 
 Derek Molter ('07)\, Chair of the Innovation Committee. The program will 
 last approximately two hours\, with dinner provided. Location: Law School
 \, Room 213.</p>
